President Donald J. Trump has announced his intention to nominate Richard M. Mills, Jr. of Texas as the Deputy Representative of the United States of America to the United Nations. Mills, a career member of the Senior Foreign Service, currently serves as the Charge dâ€™Affaires ad interim of the U.S. Embassy to Canada. He has also served as the U.S. Ambassador to Armenia and held various diplomatic roles at U.S. Embassies in Lebanon, Malta, Iraq, the United Kingdom, Saudi Arabia, and Pakistan. Mills holds a B.S. from Georgetown University, a J.D. from the University of Texas School of Law, and an M.A. from the National Defense University.

Additionally, C. J. Mahoney of Kansas has been nominated to be the Legal Adviser at the Department of State. Mahoney has served as the Deputy United States Trade Representative since March 2018 and was previously a partner at Williams & Connolly LLP, specializing in international disputes and arbitration. He also clerked for Associate Justice Anthony M. Kennedy at the Supreme Court of the United States. Mahoney holds an A.B. in Government from Harvard College and a J.D. from Yale Law School, where he was Editor-in-Chief of the Yale Law Journal.